Our little home on wheels 😍
Having a vehicle that can go just about anywhere and make a super comfortable camp in about 2 minutes is 🔥
Part of me still thinks that travel on a motorcycle is the best way to truly experience a place, but a 4x4 camper is a close second. What’s your favorite way to travel?

Morning views from camp on the edge of the Sahara Desert 🏜️ 
Which one do you prefer and why?
Enormous cacti above the morning mist. It’s hard to tell in this photo, but these are huge, probably more than 6 feet (1.8m) across. The world’s worst bean bag chair 🌵

A few years back, I had the pleasure of spending time with some Himba people in Namibia in Southern Africa. I wanted to create portraits that explore the complexities of their experience, living a somewhat traditional nomadic lifestyle in a rapidly modernizing world. In the west, many people still imagine the classic “National Geographic” version of Africa, and the reality is often very different. 

Swipe if you’re wondering if this is Photoshopped 😉

(PS. Im having to repost this because apparently the original version will melt your eyes 😱🙄)

Another from my encounter with some lovely Himba people in northeast Namibia. They are generally quite accustomed to being photographed and some actively encourage it (for a fee, of course). But it did take some convincing to make this project happen in the middle of a busy supermarket 😂

The second shot was taken not far from this market, to give you a sense of the landscape of this rural place. The stone man is one of an unknown number of sculptures by an anonymous artist that dot the landscape. They’ve become somewhat legendary amongst overland travelers in this part of the world.

A few more photographs from my project with Himba people in Namibia. These were taken in a supermarket in Opuwo, a small town in the remote northwest of the country. I’m fascinated by the ways that people hold on to their traditions in an increasingly globalized culture. Wether it’s deliberate, or simply out of habit, there are profound implications either way. This project explores that idea in one small corner of the world. 

Do any of them speak to you more than the others? Why?
